title: Health and Medical Research Council studies research fund (with photo)
content_text:
p>
    The Secretary for Food and Health, Dr York Chow, this afternoon (June 1) 
    chaired a Health and Medical Research Council meeting to discuss the 
    priority research areas and direction of the newly established Health and 
    Medical Research Fund (HMRF). The HMRF was set up in 2011 by merging two existing research funds managed 
    by the Food and Health Bureau, namely the Health and Health Services 
    Research Fund (HHSRF) and the Research Fund for the Control of Infectious

Research Fund (HHSRF) and the Research Fund for the Control of Infectious 
    Diseases (RFCID). An addition of $1 billion was injected into the HMRF to 
    broaden the scope for funding health and medical research in Hong Kong. 
    Apart from the original research ambit, the HMRF will also finance research 
    projects and facilities in areas of advanced medical research such as 
    paediatrics, neuroscience, clinical genetics and clinical trials. In the meeting, Dr Chow told the Council members that the HMRF would help to

encourage, facilitate and support local health and medical research and promote Hong Kong's position as a centre of clinical excellence in the region, through generation and application of evidence-based scientific findings. The Research Council comprises leading professionals in the local medical and academic sectors. Membership of the Research Council is as follows: Chairman
